regulatory.content:
The Central Government shall, by notification, establish a Data Protection Board of India to exercise the powers conferred on, and to perform the functions assigned to it under this Act.

The Board shall:
(a) monitor compliance with the provisions of this Act;
(b) direct the Data Fiduciary or Data Processor to adopt such measures as may be specified;
(c) inquire into data breaches and impose penalties;
(d) hear complaints from Data Principals;
(e) direct remedial measures or mitigation of data breaches.

The Board shall have the same powers as are vested in a civil court under the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908, while trying a suit, in respect of summoning and enforcing attendance of persons, requiring discovery and production of documents, and issuing commissions for examination of witnesses.

regulatory.bareActText:
18. The Central Government shall, by notification, establish a Data Protection Board of India to exercise the powers conferred on, and to perform the functions assigned to it under this Act.

19. The Board shall—
(a) monitor compliance with the provisions of this Act;
(b) direct the Data Fiduciary or Data Processor to adopt such measures as may be specified;
(c) inquire into data breaches and impose penalties;
(d) hear complaints from Data Principals;
(e) direct remedial measures or mitigation of data breaches.

20. The Board shall have the same powers as are vested in a civil court under the Code of Civil Procedure, 1908, while trying a suit, in respect of summoning and enforcing attendance of persons, requiring discovery and production of documents, and issuing commissions for examination of witnesses.

21. The Board shall consist of a Chairperson and such number of other members as the Central Government may notify.

22. The Chairperson and members of the Board shall be appointed by the Central Government.

23. The Chairperson and members of the Board shall hold office for such term and on such conditions as may be prescribed.

24. The Central Government may remove the Chairperson or any member of the Board from office in such manner and on such grounds as may be prescribed.

25. The Board may, by general or special order, regulate its own procedure.

26. No act or proceeding of the Board shall be invalid merely by reason of—
(a) any vacancy in, or any defect in the constitution of, the Board; or
(b) any defect in the appointment of a person acting as a Chairperson or member of the Board; or
(c) any irregularity in the procedure of the Board not affecting the merits of the case.

27. The Central Government may, by notification, make rules for carrying out the provisions of this Act.

28. The Central Government may, by notification, make rules to provide for—
(a) the procedure for appointment of Chairperson and members of the Board;
(b) the terms and conditions of service of the Chairperson and members of the Board;
(c) the procedure for removal of the Chairperson or any member of the Board;
(d) the procedure to be followed by the Board in the discharge of its functions;
(e) the form and manner in which complaints may be made to the Board;
(f) the form and manner in which the Board may issue directions;
(g) any other matter which is required to be, or may be, prescribed.

